entry.title: Deprecate vector<v8::Local>, part 9
entry.content:
According to V8's public API documentation, local handles (i.e.,

objects of type v8::Local) "should never be allocated on the heap".

This disallows heap-allocated data structures containing instances of

v8::Local, like std::vector>. It is unfortunate

that the V8 API itself requires the usage of such data structures.



This CL continues the deprecation of such data structures. It replaces

some vectors containing locals in API last error unittests with

stack-allocated arrays.

entry.title: Fix OpenXR Shutdown for Android
entry.content:
OpenXR shutdown on Android hits a DCHECK because we essentially try to

join a base::PlatformThread with the main browser thread. This does not

occur on other WebXR/Android runtimes because those runtimes inherit

from base::android::JavaHandlerThread. This is probably a better

interface to inherit from anyways, since we do interact with Java for

the separate Activity that is created. This change creates a new base

class to abstract out which type of Thread the RenderLoop actually

inherits from. Keeping this abstraction also requires removing the

`IsRunning` checks and redundant stops in favor of the pattern that the

other runtimes use to simply assume that the thread is always running/

started immediately after creation.



However, simply changing this threading interface is not enough as

there is now a race with when the java code shuts down. This requires

plumbing a new shutdown callback to allow the OpenXrPlatformHelper to

bubble up a forced shutdown event. This lead to a bit of bikeshedding

with renaming some callbacks/callback types to be a little bit clearer

and renaming the "onDrawingSurfaceDestroyed" event to simply

"onJavaShutdown", which is more accurate for the various cases in which

it is now used.



Bug: 1498579

breadcrumbs' factory wasn't built until later (which is disallowed via a

DumpWithoutCrashing check).



This reland handles that case by passing `IsEnabled()` a nullptr when

`g_browser_process` is null, and making `IsEnabled()` disable

breadcrumbs for the rest of the session if it's passed a nullptr. The

previous "enable for testing" toggle in breadcrumbs_status.cc was

combined with this logic into a single "breadcrumbs enabled mode" enum

that can be "from local prefs", "force enabled", or "force disabled".



[1] https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1486295



Original change's description:

> breadcrumbs: graduate from field trial

>

> This change enables breadcrumbs crash logging client-side rather than

> via field trial.

>

> Currently, breadcrumbs is enabled on 5% of Stable and 50% of

> pre-Stable channels via field trial. It will be kept at 5% of Stable

> indefinitely and considered "launched", as there's no need to collect

> breadcrumbs on every client (5% is expected to be enough).

> Specifically, this CL will enable breadcrumbs on:

> * 99% of Canary

> * 80% of Dev and Beta

> * 5% of Stable

>

> Because field trial is not intended to be used indefinitely, this

> change uses a simple random function to decide whether to log

> breadcrumbs. Breadcrumbs will stay enabled or disabled for a month

> before re-rolling, so the same users don't always incur the overhead

> of logging (which is relatively small, but still).

entry.title: media/gpu/v4l2: Clean up V4L2StatefulVD FindH264FrameBoundary()
entry.content:
https://crrev.com/c/4996628 started adding code to V4L2StatefulVD to

support multiple H.264 frame boundaries per DecoderBuffer. The code

made a mistaken assumption: that when the parsed H.264 NALU is a

k(Non)IDRSlice, the code returned 0 if it had not found a new frame,

which will cause the caller to assume that the whole DecoderBuffer

was a fragment of a new frame, but that's not necessarily true (*).

So this CL tries to clean up the return value semantics, and makes it

a pair indicating

- Whether there's a new frame's boundary found and

- The location of such frame boundary, if found, or the size of the

first fragment otherwise.

entry.title: Standardize fuzziness of fast/forms/* picker appearance tests
entry.content:
This CL modifies all tests matching [1], and standardizes their

fuzziness to:







There are a few other small changes to whitespace line endings and

such, which were added by VSCode when I did the regex replace.

Otherwise, the only change should be adding the above meta tag,

or modifying the existing one.



Many of these tests seem to fail with off-by-one pixel type mismatches

and sometimes these mismatches happen along long edges, such that many

pixels are affected. For example, see [2], for the

datetimelocal-picker-appearance.html test. It has off-by-one pixel

errors along both edges of the picker, giving 632 total pixels that

are off by a max channel difference of 1.



This CL allows up to 1000 such pixels. None of these picker tests

should be testing perfect color match of anything in the picker. They

typically test the overall layout and color, so it's ok to be off

by just 1-3 pixel values across a large number of pixels. It would

be a mistake to increase the max channel difference beyond 3, though,

since these tests *do* test that the correct shades of colors like

blue are used.

entry.title: Don't call SetJavaException() on JNI exceptions
entry.content:
This is redundant with JavaExceptionReporter, which WebView installs as

a global uncaught exception handler on initialization.



There are two upsides to removing this call:



- It avoids an unnecessary JNI back-and-forth during JNI exception

handling.

- In Cronet, which has no use for any of this (it doesn't use Crashpad

and doesn't install JavaExceptionReporter), this avoids unnecessary

work altogether.



This also makes the code paths clearer as there is now only one way that

Java exception information is reported.



The only downside is, the app developer might have decided to replace

the uncaught exception handler by a different one that doesn't call

JavaExceptionReporter - we will not get JNI exception information in

Crashpad in that case. That said, one could argue that this simply makes

the behavior of JNI exceptions consistent with how "normal" uncaught

Java exceptions would be handled anyway.

entry.title: Clarify some naming and ptr arithmetic in IOBufferPool::Internal
entry.content:
While working on a net::IOBuffer change, there was some confusion

about how the various pointers and sizes interacted with each other.

In particular. the term "Buffer" might apply to:



- the actual range of bytes to be transferred, or

- the net::IOBuffer describing this range, or

- the Internal::Buffer class extending net::IOBuffer, or

- the entire chunk of memory containing a wrapper plus the

above objects.



Hence, the term buffer_size wasn't specific enough given the

above possibilities. Instead, introduce the term "data area" for

the actual range of bytes to be transferred, and `data_area_size`

for its size.



Also a helper method and use stricter typing to clarify the situation.

entry.title: content: Skip deferring main frame updates for RenderDocument
entry.content:
With RenderDocument + compositor reuse, we swap in a new frame which

reuses the previous frame's compositor. The compositor needs to start

with BeginMainFrames paused to avoid flashing a blank frame. This is

done in WebViewImpl::DidAttachLocalMainFrame().



The same functionality also exists in DidChangeRootLayer() which is

dispatched when the Document is being detached. This is incorrect if

the compositor has already been passed to the new widget with

RenderDocument + compositor reuse. It is also unnecessary because it

will be done in DidAttachLocalMainFrame().

#3 0x55931007ab39 in blink::FontCache::GetFontPlatformData(blink::FontDescription const&, blink::FontFaceCreationParams const&, blink::AlternateFontName) third_party/blink/renderer/platform/fonts/font_cache.cc:150:37

saturated cast for clamping behavior.



Note to reviewers, please look at this carefully. I don't know if this

is the correct fix, or whether you all want to handle larger values

differently. E.g. should the value instead be stored as a float? That

would avoid clamping, but I'm assuming the rounding behavior is

desirable for more caching? Making the type a float but storing

std::round(font_size * kFontSizePrecisionMultiplier) might also work?

entry.title: Auto-verify setting should not inherit 3rd-party cookie blocking state
entry.content:
At rollout, the Auto-verify content setting (defined as "ANTI_ABUSE")

inherited the user's 3rd party cookie blocking setting. This was because

the Auto-verify setting controls the Private State Tokens API and we

wanted to ensure that if someone already had 3PC turned off at that

point, we weren't loosening that cross-site data sharing ability.



However, with the introduction of the 3rd party cookie deprecation

experiment we no longer want the Auto-verify content setting to inherit

the 3rd party cookie blocking setting. Private State Tokens (PST) were

built to replace some of the functionality of 3rd party cookies in a

more privacy preserving way, and PST is one of the APIs we want to test

during the 3PCD experiment. So we do not want PSTs to be blocked by

default for new clients during the 3PCD experiment.



This will not affect existing clients whose Auto-verify setting has

already inherited the 3PC blocking setting, or clients that have

manually blocked the Auto-verify setting. This just changes the

initialization logic for the Auto-verify setting, so that it will be

enabled by default for new clients.

entry.title: Add explicitness booleans for PixelsAndPercent fields
entry.content:
Per css-values-4 spec we should preserve the 0 unit after

simplifications, but we should not preserve it if it isn't in the

expression (e.g., min(10%, 10rem) should not be min(10% + 0px, 0% + 160px).



Currently, there is no way to indicate that in
